      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-informatics-data-format-conversion/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "As the LOTUS data volume is expected to increase over time, a frozen (as of 2021-12-20), tabular version of this dataset with its associated metadata is made available at https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5794106 (Rutz et al., 2021a). All subsequent iterations including new data sources, either updated information from the same data sources or new data, will involve a comparison with the previously gathered data at the SSOT level to ensure that the data is only curated once.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes the Single Source of Truth (SSOT) approach which avoids re-processing already curated data, supporting the 'when NOT to use' guidance.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-7554-elife-70780",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-informatics-data-format-conversion",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: Input is already a validated, deduplicated unique structure table",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:35:04.798735+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-informatics-data-format-conversion/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Allowed structural fields for the sources were divided into two types: structural (InChI, SMILES) or nominal (chemical name, not necessarily IUPAC). If multiple fields were present, structural identifiers were preferred over structure names. Among structural identifiers, when both identifiers were present, SMILES was preferred over InChI.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper confirms that the workflow handles InChI and SMILES as primary structural formats, with conversion between them. Other formats (MOL, SDF) are not explicitly mentioned as handled in the main workflow.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-7554-elife-70780",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-informatics-data-format-conversion",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: Raw data contains chemical structures in formats other than SMILES (e.g., MOL, SDF) without a prior conversion step",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:35:04.798735+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-sanitization-and-validation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The chemical sanitization step sought to standardize the representation of chemical structures coming from different sources. It consisted of three main stages (standardizing, fragment removal, and uncharging) achieved via the MolVS package. The initial standardizer function consists of six stages (RDKit Sanitization, RDKit Hs removal, Metals Disconnection, Normalization, Acids Reionization, and Stereochemistry recalculation)... In a second step, the FragmentRemover functionality was applied using a list of SMARTS to detect and remove common counterions and crystallization reagents sometimes occurring in the input DB. Finally, the Uncharger function was employed to neutralize molecules when appropriate.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes chemical structure sanitization using MolVS (not a custom sanitizing.py script), with RDKit as the underlying library. The process includes standardization, fragment removal, and uncharging\u2014matching the card's description of removing invalid entries and correcting structural defects.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-7554-elife-70780",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-sanitization-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Validate and standardize chemical structures represented as SMILES strings by removing invalid entries, correcting structural defects, and deduplicating to produce a curated set of chemically sound unique identifiers.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:35:29.653719+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-sanitization-and-validation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The chemical sanitization step sought to standardize the representation of chemical structures coming from different sources. It consisted of three main stages (standardizing, fragment removal, and uncharging) achieved via the MolVS package.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper performs chemical structure sanitization but uses the MolVS package (via Python/RDKit), not a custom script named 'sanitizing.py'. The lotus-processor repository exists and contains sanitization logic, but the paper does not explicitly name or reference a 'sanitizing.py' file. The functional role (structure sanitization) is present, but the specific tool name is not confirmed in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-7554-elife-70780",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-sanitization-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "sanitizing.py from https://github.com/lotusnprod/lotus-processor",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:35:29.653719+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-sanitization-and-validation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "InChI were translated to SMILES using the RDKit, 2021 implementation in Python 3.8 (src/2_curating/2_editing/structure/1_translating/inchi.py). They were first converted to ROMol objects which were then converted to SMILES... The chemical sanitization step sought to standardize the representation of chemical structures coming from different sources... achieved via the MolVS package.",
      "asbval:note": "RDKit is explicitly named and used for SMILES translation and structure processing. MolVS (which wraps RDKit) is used for sanitization. RDKit is confirmed as the underlying chemistry library.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-7554-elife-70780",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-sanitization-and-validation",
